<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
Widespread in the West Indies, also reported from Mexico, Ecuador, Chile, and has recently dispersed (probably via accidental human introduction) to French Polynesia and Tonga (
<bibRefCitation author="Bickel, DJ" journalOrPublisher="Bishop Museum Occasional Papers" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="14 - 20" refId="B6" refString="Bickel, DJ, 2000. New World Achradocera in Hawai'i, Tonga, and French Polynesia, with discussion of the genus (Diptera: Dolichopodidae). Bishop Museum Occasional Papers 64: 14 - 20" title="New World Achradocera in Hawai'i, Tonga, and French Polynesia, with discussion of the genus (Diptera: Dolichopodidae)." volume="64" year="2000">Bickel 2000</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="0" pageNumber="57" type="remarks">
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Remarks.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="0" pageNumber="57">
<bibRefCitation author="Aldrich, JM" journalOrPublisher="Kansas University Science Bulletin" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="75 - 94" refId="B3" refString="Aldrich, JM, 1902. Dolichopodidae of Grenada, W.I. Kansas University Science Bulletin 1: 75 - 94" title="Dolichopodidae of Grenada, W. I." volume="1" year="1902">Aldrich (1902)</bibRefCitation>
synonymized 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Dolichopodidae" genus="Achradocera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Achradocera apicalis" order="Diptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">Achradocera apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Aldrich) with 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. barbata" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="barbata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">A. barbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Loew), primarily due to the distinctive femoral coloration of both species. 
<bibRefCitation DOI="https://doi.org/10.5479/si.00810282.185" author="Robinson, H" journalOrPublisher="Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="1 - 141" refId="B67" refString="Robinson, H, 1975. Bredin-Archbold-Smithsonian Biological Survey of Dominica, the family Dolichopodidae with some related Antillean and Panamanian species (Diptera). Smithsonian Contributions to Zoology 185: 1 - 141, DOI: https://doi.org/10.5479/si.00810282.185" title="Bredin-Archbold-Smithsonian Biological Survey of Dominica, the family Dolichopodidae with some related Antillean and Panamanian species (Diptera)." url="https://doi.org/10.5479/si.00810282.185" volume="185" year="1975">Robinson (1975)</bibRefCitation>
considered 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. apicalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">A. apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
distinct by the much shorter antenna of the male. 
<bibRefCitation author="Bickel, DJ" journalOrPublisher="Bishop Museum Occasional Papers" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="14 - 20" refId="B6" refString="Bickel, DJ, 2000. New World Achradocera in Hawai'i, Tonga, and French Polynesia, with discussion of the genus (Diptera: Dolichopodidae). Bishop Museum Occasional Papers 64: 14 - 20" title="New World Achradocera in Hawai'i, Tonga, and French Polynesia, with discussion of the genus (Diptera: Dolichopodidae)." volume="64" year="2000">Bickel (2000)</bibRefCitation>
followed 
<bibRefCitation author="Aldrich, JM" journalOrPublisher="Kansas University Science Bulletin" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="75 - 94" refId="B3" refString="Aldrich, JM, 1902. Dolichopodidae of Grenada, W.I. Kansas University Science Bulletin 1: 75 - 94" title="Dolichopodidae of Grenada, W. I." volume="1" year="1902">Aldrich (1902)</bibRefCitation>
and treated 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. apicalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">A. apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. barbata" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="barbata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">A. barbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
as synonyms, based again in part on femoral coloration and variation in male antennal length. However, comparison of photos of the holotype of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. barbata" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="barbata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">A. barbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(MCZ) and specimens from North America (Alabama, Florida, Georgia, Indiana, Kentucky, Missouri, New York, Pennsylvania, Texas, South Carolina, Virginia) with 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. apicalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">A. apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the West Indies (Dominica, Montserrat, Nevis, St. Lucia, St. Vincent) reveals that these species are distinct, most notably in the form of the male front tarsus and genitalia (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Tarsus I and terminalia of males A Achradocera apicalis (Aldrich), tarsus I, posterior view (Montserrat) B Achradocera barbata (Loew), tarsus I, posterior view (Kentucky, USA), arrows indicate ventral setae C Achradocera apicalis, tip of abdomen, left lateral (Montserrat) D Achradocera barbata, tip of abdomen, left lateral (Florida, USA). Scale bars: 0.25 mm (A, B), 0.5 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.966.55192.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/450942" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">18</figureCitation>
). The 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. barbata" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="barbata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">A. barbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
type and male specimens from North America all have a distinct series of ventral setae on tarsus I (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Tarsus I and terminalia of males A Achradocera apicalis (Aldrich), tarsus I, posterior view (Montserrat) B Achradocera barbata (Loew), tarsus I, posterior view (Kentucky, USA), arrows indicate ventral setae C Achradocera apicalis, tip of abdomen, left lateral (Montserrat) D Achradocera barbata, tip of abdomen, left lateral (Florida, USA). Scale bars: 0.25 mm (A, B), 0.5 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.966.55192.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/450942" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">18B</figureCitation>
) whereas specimens from the West Indies (including syntypes from St. Vincent) lack these setae (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Tarsus I and terminalia of males A Achradocera apicalis (Aldrich), tarsus I, posterior view (Montserrat) B Achradocera barbata (Loew), tarsus I, posterior view (Kentucky, USA), arrows indicate ventral setae C Achradocera apicalis, tip of abdomen, left lateral (Montserrat) D Achradocera barbata, tip of abdomen, left lateral (Florida, USA). Scale bars: 0.25 mm (A, B), 0.5 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.966.55192.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/450942" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">18A</figureCitation>
). The surstylus and phallus are also very different, with 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. barbata" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="barbata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">A. barbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
having the surstylus enlarged and rounded apically and phallus dorsally serrate (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Tarsus I and terminalia of males A Achradocera apicalis (Aldrich), tarsus I, posterior view (Montserrat) B Achradocera barbata (Loew), tarsus I, posterior view (Kentucky, USA), arrows indicate ventral setae C Achradocera apicalis, tip of abdomen, left lateral (Montserrat) D Achradocera barbata, tip of abdomen, left lateral (Florida, USA). Scale bars: 0.25 mm (A, B), 0.5 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.966.55192.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/450942" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">18D</figureCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bickel, DJ" journalOrPublisher="Bishop Museum Occasional Papers" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="14 - 20" refId="B6" refString="Bickel, DJ, 2000. New World Achradocera in Hawai'i, Tonga, and French Polynesia, with discussion of the genus (Diptera: Dolichopodidae). Bishop Museum Occasional Papers 64: 14 - 20" title="New World Achradocera in Hawai'i, Tonga, and French Polynesia, with discussion of the genus (Diptera: Dolichopodidae)." volume="64" year="2000">Bickel 2000</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 1a) but in 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. apicalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">A. apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
the surtylus is smaller and pointed apically and the phallus is not serrate (Fig. 
<figureCitation captionStart="Figure 18" captionStartId="F18" captionText="Figure 18. Tarsus I and terminalia of males A Achradocera apicalis (Aldrich), tarsus I, posterior view (Montserrat) B Achradocera barbata (Loew), tarsus I, posterior view (Kentucky, USA), arrows indicate ventral setae C Achradocera apicalis, tip of abdomen, left lateral (Montserrat) D Achradocera barbata, tip of abdomen, left lateral (Florida, USA). Scale bars: 0.25 mm (A, B), 0.5 mm (C, D)." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.966.55192.figure18" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/450942" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">18C</figureCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Bickel, DJ" journalOrPublisher="Bishop Museum Occasional Papers" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="14 - 20" refId="B6" refString="Bickel, DJ, 2000. New World Achradocera in Hawai'i, Tonga, and French Polynesia, with discussion of the genus (Diptera: Dolichopodidae). Bishop Museum Occasional Papers 64: 14 - 20" title="New World Achradocera in Hawai'i, Tonga, and French Polynesia, with discussion of the genus (Diptera: Dolichopodidae)." volume="64" year="2000">Bickel 2000</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 1e as 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. barbata" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="barbata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">A. barbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
). The antennal length in males of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. apicalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">A. apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is highly variable, as noted by 
<bibRefCitation author="Bickel, DJ" journalOrPublisher="Bishop Museum Occasional Papers" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="14 - 20" refId="B6" refString="Bickel, DJ, 2000. New World Achradocera in Hawai'i, Tonga, and French Polynesia, with discussion of the genus (Diptera: Dolichopodidae). Bishop Museum Occasional Papers 64: 14 - 20" title="New World Achradocera in Hawai'i, Tonga, and French Polynesia, with discussion of the genus (Diptera: Dolichopodidae)." volume="64" year="2000">Bickel (2000)</bibRefCitation>
, but in all available specimens is distinctly shorter than the antenna in males of 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. barbata" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="barbata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">A. barbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Therefore, 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. apicalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">A. apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Aldrich) is here removed from synonymy with 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. barbata" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="barbata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">A. barbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(Loew). The species described in 
<bibRefCitation author="Bickel, DJ" journalOrPublisher="Bishop Museum Occasional Papers" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" pagination="14 - 20" refId="B6" refString="Bickel, DJ, 2000. New World Achradocera in Hawai'i, Tonga, and French Polynesia, with discussion of the genus (Diptera: Dolichopodidae). Bishop Museum Occasional Papers 64: 14 - 20" title="New World Achradocera in Hawai'i, Tonga, and French Polynesia, with discussion of the genus (Diptera: Dolichopodidae)." volume="64" year="2000">Bickel (2000)</bibRefCitation>
as 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. barbata" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="barbata">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">A. barbata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is 
<taxonomicName genus="A." lsidName="A. apicalis" pageId="0" pageNumber="57" rank="species" species="apicalis">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="57">A. apicalis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
